{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487070"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"244"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/244"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.06,0.43,0.1,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86354"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/244"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70632"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2198"},{"type":"tags","id":"2199"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42986"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86354"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to a new General Practice clinic complaining of severe radicular leg pain. He underwent a lumbar discectomy for a herniated disc one year ago. He has no other significant medical history. His only medication is regular opioids, currently taking 340 mg of oral morphine equivalent daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe reports dissatisfaction with his previous doctor as his pain has become worse despite escalating opioid doses. The pain has spread diffusely to involve his lower back, and even light touches can trigger painful \u0027spasms\u0027. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Recent follow-up imaging shows no progression of disc pathology or new degenerative changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most accurate regarding this patient\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["There is sufficient evidence to suspect opioid addiction and the patient should be rapidly weaned","The patient is demonstrating a pattern of physiological tolerance and his opioid dose should be increased to treat his pain","Reducing the patient\u0027s opioid dose and using non-opioid agents may improve his pain scores","There is unlikely to be benefit in trialling this patient on a similar dose of transdermal buprenorphine","His pattern of pain spread and the presence of allodynia makes a diagnosis of opioid-induced hyperalgesia unlikely"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s description of increasing pain with escalating opioid doses suggests he has developed opioid-induced hyperalgesia (OIH). \u003Cstrong\u003EReducing the patient\u0027s opioid dose and using non-opioid agents\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management strategy. OIH is characterised by the progressive development of paradoxical exacerbation of pain by opioid analgesics. It may also feature allodynia in addition to hyperalgesia, and the pain may spread beyond the initial site with poorly-defined quality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe patient is demonstrating a pattern of physiological tolerance\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While tolerance is a common phenomenon with chronic opioid use where higher doses are needed to achieve the same analgesic effect, the key difference is that with tolerance, increased doses will still provide pain relief. In this case, the patient\u0027s pain is paradoxically worsening despite dose escalation, which is characteristic of OIH rather than tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere is sufficient evidence to suspect opioid addiction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect and potentially harmful. While addiction should always be considered in patients on long-term opioids, diagnosis requires specific evidence that is not present here: impaired control over drug use, continued use despite harm, craving, and prioritising opioid use over other activities. The patient\u0027s presentation is better explained by OIH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThere is unlikely to be benefit in trialling this patient on a similar dose of transdermal buprenorphine\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Buprenorphine can be particularly effective in managing OIH due to its partial mu-opioid receptor agonist and kappa-opioid receptor antagonist properties. These unique pharmacological properties mean it is less likely to cause or worsen OIH compared to full agonists like morphine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHis pattern of pain spread and the presence of allodynia makes a diagnosis of opioid-induced hyperalgesia unlikely\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In fact, these features strongly support the diagnosis of OIH. The spread of pain beyond the original site and development of allodynia (pain from normally non-painful stimuli) are hallmark features that help distinguish OIH from other pain syndromes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManaging OIH involves gradual opioid weaning, rotation onto other agents (including buprenorphine or methadone), using opioid-sparing agents (like pregabalin, tramadol or ketamine), and engaging multidisciplinary care across physical, psychological, and interventional therapies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid-induced hyperalgesia is characterised by paradoxical worsening of pain with escalating opioid doses.","Features of opioid-induced hyperalgesia include pain spread beyond the initial site and allodynia.","Management involves opioid weaning and transition to alternative agents with multidisciplinary support."],"references":["Lee M, Silverman SM, Hansen H, et al. A Comprehensive Review of Opioid-Induced Hyperalgesia. Pain Physician. 2011;14:145-61. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21412369/","Yi P, Pryzbylkowski P. Opioid Induced Hyperalgesia. Pain Med. 2015;16 Suppl 1:S32-S36. doi:10.1111/pme.12914"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70632"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"244"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70632"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-20T20:27:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-20T20:28:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"244"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86354"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":